# Shell scripts must keep LF endings or they break under sh on macOS/Linux.
*.sh    text eol=lf
*.ps1   text eol=crlf

# chezmoi renders a template's bytes verbatim, so the SOURCE eol leaks into the
# rendered file. A stray CR breaks bash line-continuations (a `\` then CR escapes
# the CR, not the newline, aborting the script). Keep all templates LF; only
# PowerShell templates keep CRLF.
*.tmpl      text eol=lf
*.ps1.tmpl  text eol=crlf

# Nushell sources and TOML configs are read verbatim too; a stray CR makes
# Nushell choke on a sourced function and can confuse strict TOML parsers.
*.nu        text eol=lf
*.toml      text eol=lf

# theme.toml is a single-value file (the active tinty scheme) edited independently
# on every machine, so any two picks collide on the same line. The theme-pick merge
# driver (configured by the justfile: `cp -f %B %A`) auto-resolves by taking the
# INCOMING side. Under `just push` (pull --rebase) the incoming side is the local
# commit being replayed — i.e. the theme you just picked wins and the push never
# conflicts. On a machine with no local pick the pull fast-forwards and the remote
# theme lands normally, so the net effect is "last picked theme wins".
home/.chezmoidata/theme.toml merge=theme-pick

# The wezterm background.png is committed as a runtime artifact; mark PNGs binary
# so git never applies text/CRLF normalization and corrupts the image bytes.
*.png   binary
*.png   -text
